<div class="showcase">
  <div class="headline">
    <h1>Hubskip</h1>
    <p>Hubskip helps you find the destinations that match your interest while getting you the best price for your flight.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="showcase-picture" style="background-image: url('/_/images/static/showcase/hubskip.jpg'); height: 382px"></div>
</div>
<div class="arkush">
  <div class="project-body">
    <h2>Project description</h2>
    <p>
      Hubskip sells city trips to all major destinations in world. They focus on a prediction system for flight prices.
      StarterSquad developed the online shop, including search, payment and integration with several b2b providers.
    </p>
    <p>
      Within 8 weeks we have built the full solution, right on time to
      <a href="http://blog.hubskip.com/post/45383254282/launch-festival-theres-nothing-quite-like-it">demo</a>
      at <a href="http://festival.launch.co/">the Launch Festival 2013</a>
    </p>

    <div class="diptych">
      <div class="diptych-inner">
        <div class="diptych-section">
          <h2>Front-end</h2>
          <p>The&nbsp;front-end is&nbsp;based on our <a href="https://github.com/StarterSquad/angularjs-requirejs-seed">AngularJS&nbsp;+&nbsp;RequireJS&nbsp;seed&nbsp;project</a>. The&nbsp;combination of RequireJS and Angular allows us to&nbsp;build large code bases without worrying about ordering in&nbsp;the&nbsp;script tags. In&nbsp;addition it allows for compression of the&nbsp;javascript into a&nbsp;single or several minified files.</p>
          <p>AngularJS helped us to&nbsp;keep the application code _really_ simple. Some&nbsp;metrics: max number of lines in a&nbsp;single controller is 257, average number is 91 lines and the median is less then 50 lines! You&nbsp;can&nbsp;say: "Yea,&nbsp;bla-bla... These guys moved most of their logic to services then". Nope. Maximum service file size is 129 lines and average is 51. Can&nbsp;you&nbsp;say&nbsp;<a href="/_/images/posts/kiss.jpg" target="_blank">KISS</a>?</p>
        </div>
        <div class="diptych-section">
          <h2>Back-end</h2>
          <p>The REST backend was done in Scala with Spray.</p>
          <p>It was a hard choice among various technologies, but in the end the deciding factor was the fact that both <strong>S</strong>cala and <strong>S</strong>pray begin with the letter <strong>S</strong>.
            As usual we were right - they made a perfect fit.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

